Now I have a good picture of what was done:

1. **Task 1**: Added ID discovery hints to `state graph` subcommands — when you run `state graph clusters` (or any other graph subcommand) without an ID, it now prints a tip showing you how to discover valid IDs: `state tail`, `state graph hotspots`, `state evals`, `state patches`. This is a small usability fix — the equivalent of putting "You are here" markers on a map that previously just said "enter a destination."

2. **Task 2**: Added `is_token_backed()` method to `DeepSeekUsage` — this checks whether the usage struct has real cached tokens with concrete counts, vs. being zeroed out or containing placeholder values. This matters because `cache_hit_ratio()` can return 0.0 either because there were genuinely no cache hits OR because the provider didn't report cache metrics at all — and those are very different situations. The method lets you tell them apart.

3. **Task 3**: Added `--by-session` flag to `state failures tools` — groups tool failures by session ID so you can see which sessions had the most tool-level problems, rather than just a flat chronological list of every failure.

